Next, we find the first derivative $f'(x)$ using the chain rule. The derivative of $(1-x)^{-3}$ is:

$$
\begin{aligned}
f'(x) &= -3(1-x)^{-4} \times \frac{d}{dx}(1-x) \\
f'(x) &= -3(1-x)^{-4} \times (-1) \\
f'(x) &= 3(1-x)^{-4}
\end{aligned}
$$

Now, evaluate at $x=0$:

$$f'(0) = 3(1-0)^{-4} = 3(1) = 3$$

